arch:property.oc:show_val: The fauna recovered from dry sieving and, to a lesser extent, the 4mm flotation samples are dominated by long bone fragments from sheep-sized animals. Occasional cattle-sized long bone fragments are also present. The material from the dry sieve has very few vertebra fragments, but all the samples generally contain a range of skeletal elements. A number of bones identified as perinatal caprine probably all come from one individual. Bones from this animal were recovered in both the dry sieve and the flotation samples. Other than a perinatal metacarpal, which appears slightly larger and may come from a separate individual, all the perinatal bones are burnt which suggests that this process took place whilst the bones were still articulated. The presence of unfused vertebral epiphyses in flotation sample 3 shows the incorporation of at least some bones from subadult animals. Most of the rest of the material is fused and only permanent molars with a moderate amount of wear were recovered. Approximately 30-40% of the material shows evidence of burning and mostly at a low temperature. Occasional bones show evidence of being digested including some of the burnt fragments indicating the burning was postdepositional. The condition of the bone is moderately fragmented and weathering is limited. This unit seems to contain the remains of moderately processed animal carcasses, except for the perinatal caprine, which shows no evidence of beining consumed. Also there appear to be a number of fragments of a burnt adult caprine skull. Dog and pig are present as well but only forming a very small proportion of the material. The recovery of a large quantity of fish bones (mainly jaws) from sample 2 and a few from sample 3 indicates that separate disposal events took place and the whole deposit is is not totally homogeneous. Flotation samples were recorded for diagnostics only. Last number=154

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
